From cou.: 6 The solid–fluid transition may be investigated during macroscopic rheological experiments by subjecting the material to a controlled stress ramp and monitoring its response (the rate of shear ). Prior to yielding negligibly small shear rates are measured whereas above the yield point non-zero values are recorded which allows one to “guess” the yield point.
From Soup: 6 The solid–fluid transition may be investigated during macroscopic rheological experiments by subjecting the material to a controlled stress ramp and monitoring its response (the rate of shear ). Prior to yielding negligibly small shear rates are measured whereas above the yield point non-zero values are recorded which allows one to “ guess ” the yield point.
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 We illustrate such measurements performed on a controlled stress rheometer (Mars III from Thermo Fischer Scientific) equipped with a serrated plate–plate geometry with three chemically and micro-structurally distinct yield stress materials (a commercially available mayonnaise, a commercially available mustard and an aqueous Carbopol gel very similar to the commercially available hair gels) in Fig. 2.
From Soup: 7 We illustrate such measurements performed on a controlled stress rheometer (Mars III from Thermo Fischer Scientific) equipped with a serrated plate–plate geometry with three chemically and micro-structurally distinct yield stress materials (a commercially available mayonnaise, a commercially available mustard and an aqueous Carbopol gel very similar to the commercially available hair gels) in Fig. 2 .
