From cou.: 15 To overcome the difficulties in capturing the underlying physics of yielding via rheological tests, several phenomenological macroscopic models have been proposed.13,16–22 The common feature of these models is the quantity ā(t), the volume fraction of the unyielded material at time t whose time evolution is directly related to the applied stress via an evolution equation in the form . Thus, as the applied stress is increased, ā(t) varies smoothly from 1 to 0 and the combined solid and fluid rheological responses are weighted accordingly into a constitutive relation.
From Soup: 15 To overcome the difficulties in capturing the underlying physics of yielding via rheological tests, several phenomenological macroscopic models have been proposed. 13,16–22 The common feature of these models is the quantity ā ( t ), the volume fraction of the unyielded material at time t whose time evolution is directly related to the applied stress via an evolution equation in the form . Thus, as the applied stress is increased, ā ( t ) varies smoothly from 1 to 0 and the combined solid and fluid rheological responses are weighted accordingly into a constitutive relation.
